de.esoco.lib.property

Enum LayoutType

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<LayoutType>
      • de.esoco.lib.property.LayoutType
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<LayoutType>

    public enum LayoutType
extends java.lang.Enum<LayoutType>
    Enumeration of the layout types for UI element containers. The layout defines how elements will be arranged in the generated user interface. Not all layouts may be supported by an implementation but in that case it should fall back to a reasonable default placement of elements. The possible values are:
    • TABLE: Data elements are placed in the cells of a table-like structure.
    • DOCK: Elements are arranged around the edges of a center element. The size and orientation (horizontal or vertical) of the surrounding must be set as UI properties.
    • SPLIT: Like DOCK but with resizable side areas.
    • TABS: A panel with selectable tabs for each contained data element.
    • STACK: Like TABS but arranged as a vertical stack of collapsing stacks for each element child.
    • DECK: Like TABS but without an UI for selecting child elements. Selection must occur programmatically.
    • FILL: A single UI elements fills the available area.
    • FLOW: UI elements flow in the natural order defined by the UI context.
    • FLEX: A directional and controllable flow of elements based on the CSS Flexbox rendering.
    • GRID: Places elements in a horizontal, column-oriented grid structure according to their properties.
    • GRID_ROW: A row in a GRID layout.
    • GRID_COLUMN: A column in a GRID_ROW.
    • CSS_GRID: A two-dimensional arrangement of elements based on the CSS grid rendering.
    • LIST: Places elements in a list.
    • LIST_ITEM: A single element in a LIST layout.
    • CARD: A structured card with specific elements like title, content, actions.
    • FORM: Arranges elements according to their properties like in a GRID but in some implementations (e.g. HTML-based) with a structure that defines an explicit input form.
    • GROUP: Arranges elements in a distinctive group, typically inside a FORM.
    • MENU: A menu or some other kind of navigation structure.
    • HEADER: The header area of an application.
    • CONTENT: The main content area of an application.
    • SECONDARY_CONTENT: Additional content of an application. How this is displayed depends on the underlying UI framework. As an example this could be the back-side of a CARD layout.
    • FOOTER: The footer area of an application.
    • INLINE: Do not use a separate layout for this element but render it in-line with it's parent.
